I think you are reimplementing JUnit.

You are trying to use a Parameterized Test Case: a test case whose 
fixture is assigned by the outside, rather than on the inside. The 
standard pattern for that is as follows.

1. Add a constructor taking your fixture data.
2. Have the new constructor invoke super(testName), where testName is 
either a parameter of the new constructor or a name that you compute on 
the spot.
3. Add a suite() method that provides the fixture data for each test.
4. Override runTest() to implement the one and only one test for each 
row of fixture data.

If you need more than one test for each fixture row, then the solution 
is more complicated. Use FIT instead, or wait for my book.

Going back to your code, do this (+ add line, - remove line):

 &gt;  &gt; &gt; import junit.framework.Test;
 &gt;  &gt; &gt; import junit.framework.TestCase;
 &gt;  &gt; &gt; import junit.framework.TestSuite;
 &gt;  &gt; &gt; import junit.textui.TestRunner;
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;
 &gt;  &gt; &gt; public class FooTest extends TestCase {
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;     public static void main(final String[] args) {
+              TestRunner.run(FooTest.suite());
-              TestRunner.run(new FooTest());
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;     }
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;     public static Test suite() {
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;         final TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;         suite.addTest(new BarTest(5));
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;         return suite;
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;     }
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;     public static final class BarTest extends TestCase {
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;         public BarTest(final String testName, final int x) {
+                  super(testName);
                    this.x = x;
                }

-              public void testBar() { System.out.println(x); }
+              protected void runTest() {
                    // Implement test here
                }

 &gt;  &gt; &gt;         private final int x;
 &gt;  &gt; &gt;     }
 &gt;  &gt; &gt; }

Explanation: at runtime no one is setting the test method name, so it is 
null. Then the test runner tries to invoke the test method named &quot;null&quot; 
(or the null method -- it&#39;s one or the other) and it fails as you saw.

I think you can agree that the above changes are much less obtrusive 
than reimplementing the automatic test collecting scheme for JUnit&#39;s 
test runners.

As I said earlier, if you have more data-driven suites like this, then 
use FIT or FitNesse for testing instead. No law says FIT is just for 
Customer Tests.
